"If you are the type of person that wants to have complete control over your life, boy we have a product for you".

People dont buy what you do people buy why you do it and what you do simply serves as proof of why you do it. That is the point! I keep saying what i do with kayros not why i do it.

Martin Luther King didnt make 250 000 people show up for him. But for themselves because they prove what they believe by going there.

A commander before going back to battle kisses a wounded soldier. That is deep emotion, that is wanting the best for that soldier from the depth. "Because they would have done the same thing form me". The leader sets the tone, the leader makes the people feel like they belong.
We are not offended if we give a 250 mln bonus to ghandi. Great leaders would sacrifice the numbers to save the people, not sacrifice the people to save the numbers. Ex: a guy during a recession instead of firing some of his workers, forced a 4 week unpayed vacation on everyone and announce it as "is better that we should all suffer a little than any of us suffer a lot". And when people inside the organization felt protected from their leaders, the natural response is trust and cooperation

veal 333 class, super interesting Jose recapped the trip. Told us about Product market fit:  the 4 P (personas, problem, promice and product) and the 3 other things 1), he also described the steps [satisfaction (personas get value from the product), demand, efficiency (need to learn how to ship that product efficiently, for example he has 6 people looking over 1400 accounts that is extremely efficient)]. he also told us about the different levels of product market fit:
-nacent product market fit (3-5 customers)
-developing product market fit
-strong product market fit (people calling to sing)
-extreme product market fit (expanding to other industries, you can see this at amazon where they have verticality in so many different fields)

he also told us about the logic line. it goes somewhere along these lines: 
1) you have personas (group of people with similar characteristics)
2) they get triggered (example, parents at the airport have 
3) job to be done
4) product solution

another super interesting concept was for pricing. you need to leave 80% of the value to the customer so if i save 2h per semester per professor means that i save 200 dollars, i can ask for 40 dollars per professor, there are prob 10 professors in the math departments so 400 dollars a semester. Is that enought? I mean it covers the costs of the scanners so that from the semester afterward i can profit i guess. but are not crazy numbers for sure. Idk made me think.

reguarding interviews: 
- especially at the beginning 5-10 sales calls a day
- ask 5 why? questions and go to the root of what the person wants and there you can innovate. (example of putting a picture on the wall. you can make better nails or you can make another way to decorate the room and make the person feel home)
- put on the table a paper version of 20 features, give fake money to the customer and ask them to put the money on the most important features

CHRIS (CTO OF GOODYEAR)
he was from a completely different background. He is leading 70 000 people in a overly saturated market that is facing competition form china and find himself in a place where he must innovate or sent out of buisiness.
the cool thing is that they have some advantages like experience in making tires and data that allows them to train AI models that others cant
some of the takeaways from him were:
1) clearly stated problems - this motivates employess and allows for more innovation since you are giving them a bigger picture with the bulk goals
2) innovation can happen when you have money to do so, its very hard to get them in an alredy competitive market and old organization
3) the hardware innovation is slow and incremental, not like software
4) they cannot leave certain markets because they need cash to close down plants (250 mln to close one) and they simply dont have that
5) different times must have different goals. (When he sent Jose to San Fancisco, he gave them the wrong goals of "customers" but was too early in the process. This lead to Jose spreading too much the engieneering resources and to him "firing the customers" and focusing only on some of them

DINNER
1) talking with Jose, he was telling me how undergraduate allows to make connections. I think i underestimate this point a lot. I always think that i need to solve the problems and none can help me but the truth is that probably no worthy goal is achieved alone
2) get internships
3) open a AI CUP firm in Costa Rica (he has the connections to raise money, that is geniunly super cool)
4) he looks at how AI will improve GDP and GNI in countries. The idea beeing that AI is going to improve efficiency leading to a growth of the GDP that wasnt possible before. Super interesting and super interesting.

writing back to Francesco (love philosophical confrontation)

mmm random things that worked for me in the last period:
1) Immanuel Kant: “living with purpose” is living life according to the categorical imperative (“Act so that you treat humanity, weather in your own person or in that of another, always as an end and never as a means only”). 
2) “Extreme ownership”, this is a book but basically implies the need of taking full accountability and responsibility. really helps to take action since all that happens to you is your responsibility, waiting for a specific moment that comes from the environment looses meaning.
3) Healthy challenge from friends, having friends that encourage you to become better helps to start taking action. (its not a contradiction with the second principle, indeed getting out of your way to find those kind of friends its your responsibility)

For example, on Saturday night, I would have normally gone to bed early so I could code the next day, as I usually do. But Oli was like, "Forget that, you need to talk to a girl—it's been a month of coding non-stop!" (He's in a different league when it comes to talking to girls, by the way). In that moment, I didn't blame coding or anything else for my lack of progress in that area, and I accepted the challenge. However, I was failing miserably because I couldn't stay interested in talking to American girls for more than two minutes. Forcing myself to continue just to win the challenge would have gone against Kant's moral imperative, as I would have been using them merely as a means, not as an end. I have to admit, I got lucky meeting your Spanish group, haha. In that case, my main goal wasn't to win the challenge but to genuinely get to know you better.

Overall, these three principles not only guide me to take action but also to do so morally. I'm not asserting that this is the only way to live a fulfilling life—perhaps spending last night coding could have helped me win the competition on Tuesday, potentially leading to experiences I wouldn't have otherwise had. However, I believe that choosing friends who truly want the best for you and following the other principles gives us the greatest chance of living fully (my experience on Saturday night is an example of that).
